    <notes>
2012/11/19 [Tactrix] Updated to standardized file naming.
2024 [Analysis] Extended with tables found and verified by direct binary analysis of the
ROM dump. Address convention: XML address = file byte offset + 0x10000. ROM ID bytes
21 45 10 05 confirmed at file offset 0x020A.

This is an INVECS-II adaptive transmission. The shift-point, shift-pressure, and
shift-time tables below are the factory BASELINE/default calibration and the bounds
within which the adaptive "learning" logic is allowed to drift at runtime. Per Mitsubishi
service documentation, the actual learned values live in the TCU's volatile RAM (lost on
battery/ECU disconnect on this generation), NOT written back to this ROM - so nothing in
this file changes as the transmission "learns" your driving style. Tuning these tables
changes the baseline the adaptive logic starts from and the envelope it can move within,
not the live learned state itself.

Tables are split into two sections:
  1. CONFIRMED - address, scaling, and axis verified directly against real ROM data
     (values checked for physically sensible shape: e.g. pressure rising with load,
     shift speed increasing under power, etc).
  2. CANDIDATE / UNCONFIRMED - a real 2D/3D table header was found at this address with a
     plausible-looking axis, but the row/column dimensions and/or what the table actually
     controls have NOT been confirmed against vehicle behavior. Treat these as a
     starting point to verify in EcuFlash/TunerPro (e.g. watch the value change live via
     MUT logging while operating the corresponding function) before trusting the layout.
    </notes>

